@flexiarg t3/co-ownership-engine
@title Contribution Pathways
@sigils [🤝/共]
@audience programme-leads, community-managers, trainers
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/architectural-pair
@see t3/feedback-activation-loop, t3/expectation-scaffold
@next t3/feedback-activation-loop
@tier architecture
@confidence high
@npt-domain 2.4 Activation
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Engagement sustains because participants become co-producers, not just recipients. Where contribution pathways are absent, delivery depends on individual goodwill and decays when that goodwill is exhausted or the individual moves on.

  + context: T3 is designed as a cascade: national training produces local trainers. But cascade models risk treating trainers as delivery endpoints rather than co-owners of the practice.
  + if: You want training impact to spread beyond individual sessions and sustain over time.
  + however: Without explicit co-ownership structures — peer cohorts, contribution pathways, mentoring — community benefits are uneven and some trainers feel isolated after the programme ends.
  + then: Build co-ownership into the programme: dedicated peer cohorts, shared adaptation reviews, and a visible pathway for trainers to contribute improvements and mentor new cohorts.
  + because: Co-ownership turns individual participation into collective momentum and reduces drop-off after the initial training wave; it is the engine of normalisation.
      + mechanism: Peer cohorts and contribution pathways convert one-off participation into ongoing shared stewardship, creating distributed maintenance of the practice.
      + counterfactual: If contribution pathways are absent, engagement decays after initial delivery and the practice depends on individual goodwill.
      + applies-when: Trainers want to share adaptations and sustain activity beyond their first session.
      + does-not-apply: A centrally delivered programme with no expectation of local trainer autonomy.
      + signals: Trainers ask for peer support, express uncertainty about what happens after the course, or describe isolation.
      + evidence: "That ownership felt really important to me; and so then going on and sharing it and integrating it into my own practice" (T1); "I wouldn't have delivered that training if I hadn't had this framework" (T1); "At some point I potentially leave with that knowledge and it doesn't get used as much as it could have" (T3). COM-B: "I see the value" M=5.37 (high), "I feel positive" M=4.21 (moderate — motivation present but not fully activated into ownership).
  + next-steps:
      - Establish rotating peer cohorts with monthly check-ins.
      - Create a contribution pathway for trainers to propose updates.
      - Pair new trainers with a local or regional mentor.
  + governance:
      - practice: track cohort participation and peer-mentoring activity.
      - metric: proportion of trainers contributing back within 6 months.
